INSERT INTO `diseases` VALUES (1,'Aspergillosis','','Aspergillosis is an infection, growth, or allergic response caused by the Aspergillus fungus. \nThis fungus grows on dead leaves, stored grain, compost piles, or other decaying vegetation. \nThe Aspergillus species includes more than 150 types of mold that occur widely in the indoor and outdoor environment. \nAspergillus is commonly found as a lacy mold that grows on food','Fungal spores in the air and moldy foods','Keeping your dog healthy will keep their immune system strong, which is the main defense against fungal infections. Monitor what your dog eats and the enviornments they enter','Many medications available for treating aspergillosis have toxic side effects\nMedical professionals must insert a tube into the dog\'s trachea and infuse a solution over time. Certain medications can still be useful for systemic aspergillosis.  Please consult your veterinarian','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/aspergillosis_-_2009.jpg?la=en&hash=FF3EF76A04A89376E7C1C73155D0E6E1','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/aspergillosis-in-dogs'),(2,'Babesiosis','','Babesia infection or babesiosis refers to a tick-borne infection due to a protozoal parasite. Babesia invades mammalian red blood cells causing anemia. \nBabesia species are found worldwide, although in North America, most canine cases of babesiosis occur in the southern United States. \nBabesiosis is considered a serious threat to racing greyhounds and pit bull terriers.','Infected tick bite\nTransmitted from other infected animals is possible\nCan be transmitted before birth','Avoid areas with poor tick control\nAvoid contact with other infected animals\n','Imidocarb Diproprionate Drug\nClindamycin Drug','https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2014/07/08/13/36/scapularis-387181_960_720.jpg','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/babesiosis-in-dogs'),(3,'Blastomycosis','','Blastomycosis is a fungal disease caused by Blastomyces dermatitidis. \nThis fungus most commonly infects humans and animals through the respiratory tract. \nWhen the fungal spores are inhaled, they settle in the small airways and begin to reproduce. \nThe organism then spreads throughout the body and may infect other organs','Fungal spores in the air and moldy foods\nRare infection through open wound contamination','Avoid high risk areas, mainly around the Southeastern United States\nAvoid warm and moist environments \nImmediately clean and treat open wounds\n','Fluconazole, Itraconazole, and similar anti-fungal medications\nRadiograph and consultation by vet to check severity of disease','https://images.pexels.com/photos/3819718/pexels-photo-3819718.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&dpr=2&h=750&w=1260','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/blastomycosis-in-dogs'),(4,'Canine Coronavirus','Coronavirus','Canine coronavirus disease, known as CCoV, is a highly infectious intestinal infection in dogs, especially puppies. \nCanine coronavirus is usually short-lived but may cause considerable abdominal discomfort for a few days in infected dogs.  \nThe most typical sign associated with canine coronavirus is diarrhea, which may be accompanied by lethargy and decreased appetite.    ','Oral Contact with Infected Dog\nOral Contact with Infected Environment\nInfected Fecal Matter\nContaminated Food','Keep a lookout for common symptoms\nAvoid unsanitary or potentially infected areas','There is no specific treatment for canine coronavirus\nA vaccine is available, but requires a veterinary consultation to see if the vaccine is right for your dog','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/dog_intestine_stomach-1-01.jpg?la=en&hash=DF99C2EB9449F1615CBD5202B49D236D','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/coronavirus-disease-in-dogs'),(5,'Canine Distemper','Distemper','Distemper is a highly contagious viral disease of domestic dogs and other animals such as ferrets, skunks, and raccoons.  \nCommon symptoms involve diarrhea, vomiting, discharge, and even seizures. \nIt is an incurable, often fatal, multisystemic (affecting multiple organs) disease that affects the respiratory, gastrointestinal, and central nervous systems. \nDistemper is caused by the canine distemper virus (CDV).','Contact with an Infected Dog\nCoughing and Sneezing','A routine vaccine is administered to puppies at 8, 12, and 16 weeks of age\nAdditional vaccines can be given to adult dogs with the aid of your vet','Several anti-biotics can help treat secondary infections which occur with distemper\nHospitalization may be required\nThe best treatment is prevention through vaccines','https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1455380579765-810023662ea2?ixlib=rb-1.2.1&ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&auto=format&fit=crop&w=500&q=60','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/distemper-in-dogs'),(6,'Canine Parvovirus','Parvo','A relatively new virus, Parovirus is believed to be a mutation of feline distemper and shows nearly identical symptoms.\nThese symptoms include vomiting, diarrhea, occassionally accompanied by a lack of appetite, depression, or fever.','Infected fecal matter from another dog, both on surfaces and through injestion\nDirect contact is not necessary','A routine vaccine is administered to puppies at 8, 12, and 16 weeks of age\nAdditional vaccines can be given to adult dogs with the aid of your vet','Antibiotics, anti-inflammatories, and antispasmodic drugs must be perscribed by your veterinarian\nFluid administration and even plasma transfusions by your vet may be necessary','https://images.pexels.com/photos/1350591/pexels-photo-1350591.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&dpr=2&h=750&w=1260','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/parvovirus-in-dogs'),(7,'Clostridium','','A relatively unknown syndrome due to the bacteria Clostridium Perfringens (CP).  \nTypically seen in middle-aged and older dogs, CP can occur in any dog leading to diarrhea, vomiting, and abdominal discomfort.\nAcute CP can also involve internal hemorrhaging leading to mucus, stool, or couged up blood.','A toxin produced by the CP bacteria\nThis, like other bacteria, is acquired from the enviornment or ill-prepared food','Ensure your dog is in a clean and healthy environment\nMonitor their diet and nutrition to support healthy digestion\nPrevent your dog from eating undercooked or old food','Proper nutrition with high fiber dieting\nAntibiotic treatments\nProbiotic treaments\nHospitalization in very sever cases','https://images.pexels.com/photos/128401/pexels-photo-128401.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&dpr=2&h=750&w=1260','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/clostridial-overgrowth-enterotoxicosis-in-dogs'),(8,'Fleas','','Fleas are blood-sucking insects that have an affinity for animals.\nIn large groups, they can cause anemia.\nMany fleas also carry several diseases and potential parasites harmful to dogs, such as tapeworms.','Fleas are primarily outdoor creatures, but can travel to and live inside','Flea collars and oils have proven effective for long term prevention\nIn serious cases, enviornmental control products from your vet may be necessary','Regular coat inspections and grooming can help find and exterminate fleas\nIf your dog is suffering from a flea related disease or parasite, please consult your veterinatrian','https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1574342467132-e25a78ed99b8?ixlib=rb-1.2.1&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1236&q=80','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/flea-control-in-dogs'),(9,'Difofilaria Immitis','Heartworm','Heartworms are blood-borne parasites that infect a mosquito and transmit their offspring through a mosquito bite.\nThe larvae migrate into the dog\'s bloodstream and move to the heart ultimately causing clogs in the heart and interfering with several basic functions.  \nThis ultimately leads to shortness of breath, coughing, and similar symptoms, including heart failure.','Heartworms are only transmitted by the bite of an infected mosquito.\nOnce bitten by an infected mosquito, it can take years for symptoms to develop in a dog','Regular heartworm preventives should be used, especially in dogs who have recovered from heartworm\nCaution around high mosquito population areas','Consult your vet immediately if your dog has heartworms\nAn injectable drug, melarsomine is given to kill adult heartworms\nVarious other drugs may be given to reduce and treat side effects and kill larvae in the system','https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2020/03/06/09/17/dog-4906580_960_720.jpg','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/heartworm-disease-in-dogs'),(10,'Canine Hepatitis','Hepatitis','A viral disease accompanied by an inflammation of the liver.\nCan be diagnosed if your dog suffers from decrease appetite, cloudy eyes, discharge, and a very distinct cough.\nMore fatal case, usually in puppie, can lead to fever, abdominal pain, vomiting, and possible jaundice.','Direct contact with infected urine or discharge\nWeak and young immune systems can contract the virus more easily','A routine vaccine is administered to puppies at 8, 12, and 16 weeks of age\nAdditional vaccines can be given to adult dogs with the aid of your vet','There is no specific treatment for canine hepatitis\nAntibiotics and other medications may help to reduce symptoms until the dog\'s immune system can respond\nSome degree of hospitalization may be necessary','https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2016/01/13/00/36/boxer-dog-1136957_960_720.jpg','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/hepatitis-adenovirus-infection-in-dogs'),(11,'Canine Herpesvirus','Herpes','A disease that mostly affects puppies, Canine Herpes Virus (CHV) is a viral infection that causes thick nasal dishcharge, anorexia, crying, seizures, and sudden death.\nAdult dogs can also suffer from non-specific symtpoms such as coughing, sneezing, or even miscarriage.\n','Direct contact with an infected dog\nA puppy can be born with CHV if the mother is infected\n','Avoid contact with infected dogs, especially if the dog is pregnant\nGood hygiene for the animal and it\'s environment is key to reduce mortality rate','The most common outcome for young and developing puppies is death\nIf a puppy shows any signs, consult your vet immediately\nBloodwork from recovered females may be beneficial\nCHV eye infections can be controlled through eyedrops, antibiotics, and pain relievers','https://cdn.pixabay.com/photo/2017/09/06/21/32/dog-2723108_960_720.jpg','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/herpesvirus-in-dogs'),(12,'Histoplasmosis','','A fungal infection primarily found in young, large dogs that can lead to fever, depression, and loss of appetite.\nLabored breathing and coughing, unhealthy defacation (diarrhea or abnormal stools), and even ulcers can be signs of this infection.\nTransmitted through the inhalation of fungal spores growing from soil containing bird or bat feces.\nThis disease has been shown to very rarely be transmitted to humans.  The young, elderly, and those weakened immune systems should show caution, especially if in the same infected area.\nThe animal does not have to be segragated from the family for this reason.','Exposure to Histoplasma organisms, the longer the riskier\nWarm, moist, and infected soil, often found along large rivers and lakes','Keeping your dog healthy will keep their immune system strong, which is the main defense against fungal infections\nMonitor what your dog eats and the enviornments they enter\nLimit exposure to at risk environments, especially in hunting dogs','Anti-fungal medications such as Fluconazole and Itraconazole can be used with relatively few side ffects\nContinuous medical therapy over the course of 6 months or more\nRepeated blood tests to measure toxicity levels from medication','https://images.pexels.com/photos/963040/pexels-photo-963040.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&dpr=2&h=750&w=1260','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/canine-histoplasmosis'),(13,'Canine Ancylostoma','Hookworm','Hookworms are internal blood sucking parasites that live inside of a dog\'s intensinal walls.\nThey often result in intestinal distress and anemia.  Even after feeding, the hookworm prevents blood from clotting and causes further blood loss.\nPale gums, weakness, weight loss, dull caots, and even death in younger dogs are all signs of hookworm infection.\nA stool sample examination by your vet is the best way to properly assess hookworm infection.','Oral Ingestion\nThe worm can burrow into the dog\nThrough the mother\'s placenta before birth\nThrough the mother\'s milk','All puppies should be treated for heart hookworm at two to three weeks of age\nProper disposal of feces and prevention of ingestion\nProper deworming of puppies and nursing females\n','Anthelmintics are a medication known to eliminate hookworms\nBlood transfusions may be necessary to treat anemia\n','https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1566410845311-1201aefbee6a?ixlib=rb-1.2.1&ixid=eyJhcHBfaWQiOjEyMDd9&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1350&q=80','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/hookworm-infection-in-dogs'),(14,'Hypothyroidism','','In hypothyroidism, impaired production and secretion of thyroid hormones result in a decreased metabolic rate. This disorder is most common in dogs but also develops rarely in other species, including cats, horses, and other large, domestic animals. Most common in dogs 4-10 years of age. Another thing is that spayed females have a higher risk of developing the disease.','The Merck Veterinary Manual states that hypothyroidism is one of the most over-diagnosed diseases in dogs. This is because many diseases mimic hypothyroidism. Some conditions or clinical signs even improve with thyroid medication. Other diseases also affect the thyroid levels, but are not hypothyroidism. This can make diagnosing a thyroid condition tricky, so be patient as you work with your veterinarian to get to the root of your dog�s symptoms.\n\nYour veterinarian will diagnose your dog based on clinical signs and careful diagnostic testing. This will probably require several blood tests to determine if your dog exhibits any of the abnormalities commonly associated with the disease, and regular monitoring of your dog�s thyroid levels.\n\nOne of these tests will probably be a test of your dog\'s T4 concentration. This is a good initial screening test for hypothyroidism, however, your veterinarian may recommend running further tests to get a definitive result.','Thyroid disease in dogs requires medical treatment from a veterinarian. Make an appointment with your veterinarian if your dog is showing symptoms of thyroid disease.','Not much treatment for this disease, but Hypothyroidism is still somewhat treatable. Your veterinarian will probably give your dog a prescription for thyroxine, a replacement hormone compound, to offset your dog�s low thyroid function.\n\nThe dosage will vary depending on your dog\'s weight and thyroid levels. Your veterinarian may need to adjust your dog�s dosage over time, and you should expect to see results after one to two months. Once your veterinarian has determined a stable dose, your dog will most likely need to have his thyroid levels retested once or twice a year and continue the stable dose of medication, for the rest of his life. managed with daily thyroid hormone replacement.','https://i.pinimg.com/originals/c5/4c/db/c54cdb9981612f37e1d0c95557334068.jpg','https://www.akc.org/expert-advice/health/thyroid-disease-in-dogs/'),(15,'Canine Influenza','Dog Flu','Canine influenza (CIV) is the result of two strands of influenza, these strands were previously known to infect other species but soon made their way to dogs, they are H3N8 and H3N2','Seen as transmitted by the air, dogs can get this disease from kennel walls, floors, or even their own water bowl. ','The best way to prevent this is make sure you are keeping your dogs food bowls clean as well as getting them the vaccination.','There are a couple options available, but the main one is getting a vaccination. Contact your veteranian for other options.','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/featured-canine_influenza_the_dog_flu.jpg?h=217&w=360&la=en&hash=D620A8E7C129D5BC0DCE708AA5E52213','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/canine-influenza-the-dog-flu'),(16,'Canine Infectious Tracheobronchitis','Kennel Cough','Kennel cough is a broad term covering any infectious or contagious condition of dogs where coughing is one of the major clinical signs. It is also referred to as infectious tracheobronchitis. The term tracheobronchitis describes the location of the infection in the trachea or \'windpipe\' and bronchial tubes.','Kennel cough is very contagious, and dogs can readily transmit it by casual contact such as sniffing each other when on a walk, playing, or sharing water dishes.','Most vaccination programs your veterinarian will recommend include adenovirus and parainfluenza. Bordetella vaccination is also highly recommended for dogs that are boarded, groomed, or interact with other dogs in areas such as dog parks.','There is no specific treatment for the viral infections, but many of the more severe signs are due to bacterial involvement, particularly�Bordetella bronchiseptica. Antibiotics are useful against this bacterium.','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/featured-kennel_cough_or_tracheobronchitis_in_dogs.jpg?h=217&w=360&la=en&hash=52D9637D4C85D5F12F014856C8EAF905','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/kennel-cough-or-tracheobronchitis-in-dogs'),(17,'Lyme Disease','','Lyme disease is caused by a spirochete, Borrelia burgdorferi. A spirochete is a type of bacterium.','Lyme disease is transmitted to dogs through the bite of a tick. Once in the blood stream, the Lyme disease organism is carried to many parts of the body and is likely to localize in joints or kidneys.','The key to prevention is keeping your dog from being exposed to ticks. Ticks are found in grassy, wooded, and sandy areas. They find their way onto an animal by climbing to the top of a leaf, blade of grass, or short trees, especially cedar trees.','Because the Lyme spirochete is a bacterium, it can be treated with antibiotics. The antibiotic of choice is doxycycline, followed by amoxicillin, then azithromycin. Treatment lasts for 4 weeks. Occasionally, the initial infection will recur, or the pet will become re-infected by being bitten by another infected tick.','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/featured-ticks.png?h=225&w=360&la=en&hash=3420F8AEFE1342658B9163DE33476148','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/lyme-disease-in-dogs'),(18,'Mucormycosis','','Most of the fungi that cause mucormycosis are found within the soil. Exposure to these funguses will depend on how much time your dog spends in heavily soiled areas that have decaying vegetation. The fungus will transfer from the soil to your dog�s coat and skin. \n\n','Mucormycosis is a general class of fungi that will cause zygomycetes, pythiosis and lagenidiosis. It comes from the Mucoraceae family and is found worldwide. The fungi will feed on decaying organic material in the environment. It dwells within the soil and is easily transferred to your dog when they are outside. The fungi will attach to their coat and/or skin. Your dog can also become infected by inhaling the fungi spores or by eating a plant that has the fungi on it.�','Keepng your house sanitary, as well as making sure that you are having the veteranarian check the resperitory system of your dog each visit.','After the diagnosis has been made, your veterinarian will discuss treatment options for your dog. If your dog�s overall health has become severely debilitated from the infection, hospitalization will be recommended. While hospitalized, your dog will be continually monitored and be put on intravenous fluids as well as given nutritional therapy. In some instances, oxygen therapy may be required as well. \n\n','https://images.wagwalkingweb.com/media/articles/dog/mucormycosis/mucormycosis.jpg','https://wagwalking.com/condition/mucormycosis'),(19,'Neosporosis','','Canine neosporosis is a worldwide disease caused by the obligate intracellular parasite protozoan Neospora caninum, manifesting mainly neurological symptoms.','Eating things such as dead animals, or things that have come into contact with such.','Dogs should never have access to bovine placental materials, dead calves, fetal membranes, aborted fetuses, or raw/undercooked meat, and should be prevented from defecating around livestock. Also, contact with infected tissues of other intermediate hosts','Treatment of neosporosis is usually difficult and temporarily, partially, or completely ineffective. Please contatct your veterinarian immediately! ','https://archive.content.aah.net.au/files/images/2010-11-Daisy-in-recovery.jpg','https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6055790/'),(20,'Protothecosis','','Protothecosis is a disease which, as noted above, can affect humans, dogs, cats and cattle.  It enters the body usually through injured skin, the gastrointestinal tract or the nose and begins to develop, spreading to other parts of the body of the host like the eyes, skin or kidneys.','Eating Protothecosis is a disease which, as noted above, can affect humans, dogs, cats and cattle.  It enters the body usually through injured skin, the gastrointestinal tract or the nose and begins to develop, spreading to other parts of the body of the host like the eyes, skin or kidneys','Not letting your dogs eat things out of the sewage, or gutter of the road.','If protothecosis is found, some sort of antifungal treatment will likely be needed in an attempt to rid your family pet of the fungal infection. Most animals who are found to be afflicted with protothecosis are in a very poor condition by the time veterinary medical attention is sought.','https://images.wagwalkingweb.com/media/articles/dog/protothecosis/protothecosis.jpg?auto=compress&fit=max&ixlib=imgixjs-3.4.1&w=442','https://wagwalking.com/condition/protothecosis'),(21,'Pythiosis','','Pythiosis is the result of being infected by a water mold called Pythium insidiosum. This organism can affect the gastrointestinal tract or the skin. It appears that large breed dogs under six years of age are most commonly affected.','Spores enter the dog through various types of natural water sources exposed to the certain type of spore.','When hunting or hiking with your animal, make sure to wash them vigorously afterwards.','It is important to have all infected tissues in the body removed, whether in the skin or in the digestive tract. If a limb is involved, amputation may be required. Actively infected dogs may require hospitalization with intravenous fluid support and antibiotic therapy. It is important for these dogs to receive high calorie, high digestibility food to counter the weight loss that typically occurs.','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/pythiosis_in_dogs.jpg?la=en&hash=0CB377873FA79995543C5C9190842D22','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/pythiosis-in-dogs'),(22,'Lyssavirus','Rabies','Rabies is one of the most devastating viral diseases affecting mammals, including dogs and humans. It is a fatal disease caused by infection with the rabies virus. Rabies virus is found throughout the world, including North America, Central and South America, Asia, Africa, the Middle East, and some parts of Europe.','The infection is transmitted when one infected animal bites another. Transmission by other means is rare.','There are several rabies vaccines approved for dogs, cats, horses, and ferrets. All dogs and cats between the ages of twelve and sixteen weeks should be vaccinated. ','There is no treatment for a dog with rabies. If rabies is suspected, the dog has to be kept in isolation and prevented from escaping or injuring someone.','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/raccoon_rabies.png?la=en&hash=56899F4719D09ADFFEBE4A1912463029','https://vcahospitals.com/search-results?term=rabies'),(23,'Dermatophytosis','Ringworm','Ringworm is the common name given to a fungal infection of the superficial layers of the skin, hair, and nails. Ringworm infections can occur in humans and in all domesticated species of animals.','Ringworm is contagious and transmission occurs by direct contact with the fungus. It may be passed by direct contact with an infected animal or person, or by handling contaminated objects or touching contaminated surfaces.','Infected hairs contain numerous microscopic fungal spores that can be shed into the environment. Keep these areas of where you dog has been clean, and make sure to wash your dog often.','Regardless of the severity of the case, treatment of ringworm in dogs is always necessary to avoid the spread of infection to children or other pets. The specific method of treatment recommended by your veterinarian to treat your dog will depend on the severity of the infection','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/dog_bath.png?la=en&hash=99D3607A0DFE219560E80C52A33525A2','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/ringworm-in-dogs'),(24,'Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever','','Rocky Mountain spotted fever is a disease of humans and dogs that is caused by Rickettsia rickettsii. \n(Rickettsiae are a specialized type of bacteria that live only inside other cells.) \nRocky Mountain spotted fever organisms are only found in certain geographic areas of North, South, and Central America.','This disease is often transmitted through the bites of infected ticks. In the United States, the American dog tick and the Rocky Mountain wood tick are considered the most important transmission agents for Rickettsia rickettsii. The brown dog tick also transmits the disease in some parts of the country (including Arizona) and in other countries.','The most important preventive steps are those that control ticks, the most common source of the disease. Keeping your dog away from areas known to harbor ticks is a step you can take. Preventive medications that will keep your dog from being infested with ticks are also available from your veterinarian. Any ticks found on your dog should be promptly and properly removed to prevent the spread of disease. Remove any ticks by using fine-pointed tweezers to grasp the head of the tick (right where it enters the skin). Pull the tick straight off, making sure not to grasp or squeeze its body. If there are multiple ticks, it may be best to have your veterinarian remove them and examine your dog. It is important to remember that contact with fluids and excretions from infected ticks can spread the disease to people.','There are treatment options available, if you believe this illness it what you are looking for please CONTACT YOUR VET IMMEDIATELY','https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1511816628855-8a3d86e8f674?ixlib=rb-1.2.1&auto=format&fit=crop&w=1052&q=80','https://www.merckvetmanual.com/dog-owners/disorders-affecting-multiple-body-systems-of-dogs/rocky-mountain-spotted-fever-tick-fever-in-dogs'),(25,'Taeniasis','Tapeworm','Tapeworms are flat, segmented intestinal parasites of the cat and dog. Tapeworms belong to the cestode family of intestinal worms. There are several types of tapeworms, but the most common tapeworm species observed in dogs is Dipylidium caninum.','Unlike other intestinal parasites, dogs cannot become infected by eating fertilized tapeworm eggs.\n\nTapeworms must first pass through an intermediate host (a flea) before they can infect a dog.\n\nWhen the tapeworm eggs are released into the environment, they must be ingested by flea larvae, an immature stage of the flea. Once inside the larval flea, the tapeworm egg continues to develop as the flea matures into an adult flea.','Flea control is critical in the management and prevention of tapeworm infection. Flea control involves treating the dog and the environment. Your veterinarian can recommend a safe and effective flea control for your pet.','With today\'s deworming medications, treatment is simple and effective. The parasiticide may be given either in the form of tablets or by injection. It causes the parasite to be digested in the intestines so you normally will not see tapeworms passed in the stool. These drugs are very safe and should not cause any side effects.','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/tapewormdogflealifecycle201801scaler.jpg?la=en&hash=CAA309DF447F5588D5AA6FA6745F2836','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/tapeworm-infection-in-dogs'),(26,'Toxocariasis','Roundworm','Roundworms (also known as nematodes or ascarids) are parasites that live freely in the intestine, feeding off of partially digested intestinal contents. Their name is derived from their tubular or \"round\" shape.','Infected dogs shed the microscopic roundworm eggs in their feces. Other dogs may become infected by sniffing or licking infected feces. Roundworm eggs can also be spread by other animals such as rodents, earthworms, cockroaches, and birds. In these animals, the roundworms are merely transported, and do not mature into adults; if a dog eats this paratenic host (an accidental transport host), the roundworm is able to continue its lifecycle.','Dont feed your dog old food. Roundworms are of most concern to puppies. The most common consequence of roundworms is growth reduction. Since roundworms eat partially digested food in the intestinal tract, if there are large numbers of roundworms, they will rob the growing puppy of vital nutrients.','Treatment is simple and effective. There are many safe and effective preparations available to kill adult roundworms in the intestine. Many monthly heartworm preventives contain medications that are effective against intestinal roundworms and help prevent future infections. Some of these preparations kill only the adult worms and do not affect migrating or encysting larvae. New products have recently been developed that will also affect the larval stages. Your veterinarian will advise you on the best treatment and prevention plan for your pet.','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/roundwormlifecycledogcatupdated2018scaler.jpg?la=en&hash=187A420A89BAFFE662E3ED4C470D3085','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/roundworm-infection-in-dogs'),(27,'Trichinosis','Pork Roundworm','parasitic disease that can be transmitted to people. It is caused by a type of worm known as a nematode. The name of the disease comes from the scientific name for the worm, Trichinella spiralis. People become infected when they eat undercooked infected meat, usually pork or bear, although other animals can also be infected with this nematode. Natural infections occur in wild meat-eating animals; most mammals are susceptible.','Infection occurs when an animal eats meat with cysts containing the Trichinella larvae. The life cycle continues inside the animal, with larvae eventually migrating throughout the body, where they form cysts in muscles.','Do not let your dog eat rodents, if you live on a farm, ask your Vet about options to prevent this disease.','Treatment is generally impractical in animals.','https://www.petmd.com/sites/default/files/pork-roundworm-infection-dogs.jpg','https://www.merckvetmanual.com/dog-owners/disorders-affecting-multiple-body-systems-of-dogs/trichinellosis-trichinosis-in-dogs?query=Trichinosis'),(28,'Trichuris Vulpis','Whipworm','Whipworms are intestinal parasites that are about 1/4 inch (6 mm) long. They live in the cecum (a pouch that forms the first part of the large intestine) and large intestine of dogs, where they cause severe irritation to the lining of those organs. Whipworm infection results in watery, bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and general debilitation. Of all the intestinal parasites found in dogs, whipworms cause the most disease.','Whipworms pass microscopic eggs in the stool. The eggs are very resistant to drying and heat, so they can remain alive in the environment for up to 5 years. ','Speak to your veterinarian for best options for preventive medication.','There are several drugs that are effective against whipworms. All drugs require two treatments, spaced at a three to four week interval, to clear the infection. Speak to your Veterinarian','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/whipwormlifecycle201801scaler.jpg?la=en&hash=D8A6183B659CC8DC3BA27E94056C69A2','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/whipworm-infections-in-dogs'),(29,'Legg-Calve-Perthes Disease','','Legg-Calve-Perthes disease is also known as avascular or aseptic necrosis of the femoral head. This is a condition in which the head of the femur (the \"ball\" in the ball-and-socket joint that forms the hip) spontaneously begins to degenerate. Over time, this degeneration will cause collapse of the hip and lead to arthritis.','The exact cause of this condition is unknown. Studies suggest that disrupted blood flow to the hip may be involved and this disruption may be due to clots within the blood vessels. The bone begins to weaken and deteriorate, leading to small fractures. Over time, scar tissue may develop to stabilize the bone, however changes in the bone structure will lead to arthritis.','There are not many options to prevent this disease, some think that the disease is hereditary, that has not been confirmed, speak with your veterinarian for a case by case breakdown.','Speak to your veterinarian to discuss how far along the disease is and what options are available.','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/legg-calve-perthes_disease.png?la=en&hash=888D512719223FDB35951E02AF8D7441','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/legg-calve-perthes-disease-in-dogs'),(30,'Sebaceous Adenitis','','Sebaceous adenitis is an immune-mediated disorder in which there is an inflammatory process directed against the sebaceous glands in the skin. The sebaceous glands are associated with the hair follicles and produce the substance that helps to keep the skin supple and the haircoat soft.','There is not much to transmitting this disease, it is normally develeped on a case by case basis. Please talk to your veterinarian for more information.','For options of preventive actions please see your local veterinarian.','Unfortunately, sebaceous adenitis is a challenging disease, as the clinical signs may come and go independent of any treatment that it instituted. There are no studies to support any definitive treatment. Please see your Veterinarian immediately.','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/sebaceous_adenitis_in_dogs.png?la=en&hash=C624867466E4F24EA336ACD9A2B1A2B5','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/sebaceous-adenitis-in-dogs'),(31,'Hyperadrenocorticism','Cushing\'s Disease','Cushing\'s disease, or pituitary-dependent hyperadrenocorticism, arises from adenomatous enlargement of the pituitary gland, resulting in excessive ACTH production. A related term, Cushing syndrome, refers to elevated adrenocortical hormones, regardless of cause. The latter term includes pituitary-dependent hyperadrenocorticism as well as adrenal-dependent disease, which is associated with functional adenomas or adenocarcinomas of the adrenal gland. Ectopic ACTH secretion has not been reported in dogs; however, in people, ectopic ACTH secretion is associated with certain lung tumors. Iatrogenic hyperadrenocorticism results from chronic excessive exogenous steroid administration.','There is not much transmission for this disease. Cushing\'s disease is sometimes hereditary or can be developed and maintained to a certain degree.','Unfortunately this disease is hereditary, so there is not much to prevent the disease.','Three treatment options are available for Cushing disease in dogs. Medical, surgical, and radiation therapy have all been used with varying degrees of success.','https://nitrocdn.com/efuJsKtDyptHinJPkZsojPmTOBGlNDxZ/assets/static/optimized/rev-ce16c6e/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/Cushings-01.jpeg','https://www.merckvetmanual.com/endocrine-system/the-pituitary-gland/cushing-disease-pituitary-dependent-hyperadrenocorticism-in-animals'),(32,'Von Willebrand\'s Disease','','Von Willebrand\'s disease (vWD) is the most common inherited bleeding disorder of both humans and dogs. It is caused by a deficiency in the amount of a specific protein needed to help platelets (the blood cells used in clotting) stick together and form clots to seal broken blood vessels. The deficient protein is called von Willebrand factor (vWF).','This disease is developed when a dog has too few platelets, wounds and injuries can be really dangerous because he or she might not stop bleeding and lose a lot of excess blood.','The avoidance of certain medications is critical for the dog with known vWD. Please contact your vet to find out what medications are on this list.','In an emergency situation, transfusion of blood or fresh frozen plasma may stabilize a bleeding patient. The dog donating blood may be treated with a drug called DDAVP prior to blood collection. DDAVP will raise the level of von Willebrand factor in the donor\'s blood, an obvious benefit for the dog with vWD.\n\nSome dogs with vWD are able to increase the amount of von Willebrand factor in circulation after the administration of DDAVP, although the response is variable. At this time, it is not recommended to use this drug on a regular basis. The drug is expensive, and not all dogs will respond to it. Your veterinarian will discuss the treatment option and help you decide if it is an appropriate option for your pet\'s condition.','https://vcahospitals.com/-/media/vca/images/lifelearn-images/vonwillebrand2018scaler.jpg?la=en&hash=2A101041CCE5F6AE2051BA2D677B4CA6','https://vcahospitals.com/know-your-pet/von-willebrands-disease-in-dogs');
